    print("  - k5_complement_balancing_symmetry.txt")
    print("  - flat-split Poisson tail lemma")
    print()

    print("1. quotient balanced actions by permutation and complement")
    print(
        r"  A balanced action is \(a=\sum_g q_g\delta_g\),"
        r" \(g\in\{0,1\}^5\), with common marginal \(c(a)\)."
    )
    print(
        r"  Define \(a^c=\sum_g q_g\delta_{\mathbf 1-g}\)."
        r" Then \(a^c\) is balanced and has marginal \(1-c(a)\)."
    )
    print(
        r"  The balanced enumeration uses the quotient generated by coordinate"
        r" permutations and \(a\mapsto a^c\): the 1293 vertices reduce to 25"
        r" action classes. Thus the low-gap proof may be stated once per"
        r" permutation-complement class."
    )
    print(
        r"  Important convention: equality of residuals is a quotient/translation"
        r" identity in centered coordinates, not equality of arbitrary rank-fixed"
        r" representatives."
    )
    print()

    print("2. define curvature gaps by competing action class")
    print(
        r"  For each competing balanced action class \(a\), choose the active"
        r" Chase/Comb orbit action \(a_C\) at the packet representative and set"
        r" \["
        r"     G_a(W;x)=T_{a_C}W(x)-T_aW(x)."
        r" \]"
    )
    print(
        r"  The low-gap correction \(A(x)=-L(x)/25-P(x)/200\) is included in"
        r" \(W=V_{\rm orbit}+A\). The action-grouping certificate records each"
        r" \(G_a\) as a signed packet measure plus an affine source."
    )
    print(
        r"  The old labels \(F_i,M_i,Q_i,B_i,H_i,E_i\) are now names for"
        r" packet curvature-gap generators, not primary proof cases."
    )
    print()

    print("3. identify packet partitions with ordered-chamber faces")
    print(
        r"  Work in the ordered chamber \(x_1\ge\cdots\ge x_5\) with gaps"
        r" \(g_i=x_i-x_{i+1}\ge0\)."
    )
    print(
        r"  A packet partition \(p=(p_1,\ldots,p_m)\) is the face where"
        r" \(g_i=0\) inside each packet and \(g_i>0\) at packet boundaries."
        r" Its codimension is the number of zero gap equations."
    )
    print(
        r"  The ordered-face report rewrites every certificate row as a transition"
        r" among these faces: flat-face split, adjacent merge, packet-count change,"
        r" higher refinement, codimension-two boundary, or a finite residual face."
    )
    print()

    print("4. build the packet-face recurrence graph")
    print(
        r"  Let \(\mathcal G\) be the directed graph whose nodes are all packet"
        r" curvature-gap generators \(F_i,M_i,Q_i,B_i,H_i,E_i\) and generated"
        r" Bellman-image variables \(X_i\)."
    )
    print(
        r"  Each exact Bellman-image certificate gives an inequality"
        r" \["
        r"     G_i \le s_i+\sum_j\lambda_{ij}G_j,\qquad \lambda_{ij}\ge0."
        r" \]"
        r"  This is a discrete superharmonic inequality on \(\mathcal G\)."
    )
    print(
        r"  The graph is the packet-face analogue of the reflected ordered-chamber"
        r" finite-difference system in the four-expert comb proof."
    )
    print()

    print("5. prove boundary rows directly")
    print(
        r"  Boundary nodes are rows whose Bellman image is already discharged by"
        r" finite cone inequalities, complement symmetry, direct packet convexity,"
        r" or finite telescoping. These have explicit rational slack."
    )
    print(
        r"  In the old schema language this includes the direct rows in the"
        r" flat-split, adjacent-merge, packet-count, finite-residual,"
        r" one-one-three boundary, and higher-refinement certificates."
    )
    print()

    print("6. prove acyclic interior rows by a topological maximum principle")
    print(
        r"  Collapse \(\mathcal G\) into strongly connected components."
        r" Any acyclic component is controlled by descending induction along the"
        r" condensation graph: once all outgoing components are bounded, the"
        r" superharmonic inequality bounds the current component."
    )
    print(
        r"  This is the finite discrete maximum principle: nonnegative boundary"
        r" domination propagates through substochastic/acyclic packet-face transitions."
    )
